WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.100 --> 00:00:01.460
All right, maybe we get started.

2
00:00:03.280 --> 00:00:06.640
Good afternoon, everyone. I hope you've all been enjoying this really

3
00:00:06.760 --> 00:00:08.119
spectacular meeting this year.

4
00:00:09.160 --> 00:00:12.900
I'm Dr. Kimberly Stegmaier from the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute and Boston

5
00:00:12.940 --> 00:00:16.860
Children's Hospital, and it's my honor to serve as chair elect of the

6
00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:19.540
AACR Hematologic Malignancies Working Group.

7
00:00:20.780 --> 00:00:24.460
The American Association for Cancer Research established the AACR

8
00:00:24.540 --> 00:00:28.060
Award for Outstanding Achievement in Blood Cancer Research to honor

9
00:00:28.140 --> 00:00:32.119
individuals who have made exceptional scientific contributions to

10
00:00:32.201 --> 00:00:36.100
basic, translational, or clinical research in the field of

11
00:00:36.120 --> 00:00:38.120
blood cancers and related disorders.

12
00:00:39.150 --> 00:00:43.120
On behalf of the officers and directors of the AACR Board, I would

13
00:00:43.160 --> 00:00:46.780
like to thank AbbVie for their generous support of this prestigious

14
00:00:46.840 --> 00:00:48.050
award for the fifth year

15
00:00:49.040 --> 00:00:51.620
and their support of excellence in blood cancer

16
00:00:51.630 --> 00:00:55.480
research. This year's honoree is an outstanding

17
00:00:55.540 --> 00:00:59.000
cancer scientist whose pioneering work has transformed our

18
00:00:59.020 --> 00:01:02.200
understanding of leukemia and stem cell biology.

19
00:01:03.380 --> 00:01:07.160
His groundbreaking mechanistic and translational research has been

20
00:01:07.220 --> 00:01:10.880
instrumental in both the basic science and clinical development,

21
00:01:11.380 --> 00:01:14.780
leading to FDA approval of the stem cell mobilizing agents,

22
00:01:15.060 --> 00:01:15.840
plerixafor

23
00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:19.920
and motexafortide. I can't say that word.

24
00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:24.700
We're delighted to recognize the 2026 recipient of the

25
00:01:24.780 --> 00:01:28.400
AACR Award for Outstanding Achievement in Blood Cancer Research,

26
00:01:28.860 --> 00:01:30.500
Dr. John F. DiPersio,

27
00:01:31.520 --> 00:01:35.380
Virginia E. and Sam J. Goleman Professor of Medicine in Oncology,

28
00:01:36.240 --> 00:01:40.200
Director of the Section of Cellular Therapy and the Center for Gene

29
00:01:40.380 --> 00:01:44.030
and Cellular Immunotherapy, and former Chief of the Division of

30
00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:47.660
Oncology and Deputy Director of the Siteman Center

31
00:01:48.160 --> 00:01:51.860
at Washington University School of Medicine in St. Louis.

32
00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:56.940
Dr. DiPersio was also among the first to identify the critical role of

33
00:01:56.980 --> 00:02:00.540
JAK1/2 signaling in the pathogenesis of graft versus host

34
00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:04.000
disease. His seminal preclinical and clinical studies

35
00:02:04.020 --> 00:02:07.810
contributed directly to the FDA approval of ruxolitinib for the treatment of

36
00:02:07.860 --> 00:02:10.220
steroid-refractory acute GVH.

37
00:02:11.360 --> 00:02:15.060
His recent investigations have yielded best-in-class JAK inhibitors for the

38
00:02:15.140 --> 00:02:19.080
prevention and treatment of GVHD, as well as for the prevention of solid

39
00:02:19.180 --> 00:02:22.560
organ allograft rejection, leading to improved patient

40
00:02:22.620 --> 00:02:23.180
outcomes.

41
00:02:24.240 --> 00:02:27.760
His work has also catalyzed the development of less toxic

42
00:02:27.820 --> 00:02:31.700
antibody-based conditioning regimens for autologous and allogeneic stem

43
00:02:31.780 --> 00:02:34.980
cell transplantation and for ex vivo gene therapy.

44
00:02:36.220 --> 00:02:39.880
Dr. DiPersio and his colleagues were among the first to collaboratively

45
00:02:39.900 --> 00:02:43.860
employ whole genome sequencing to characterize clonal evolution

46
00:02:43.880 --> 00:02:47.700
in relapsed AML and subsequent extensions of this work to

47
00:02:47.740 --> 00:02:48.600
multiple myeloma.

48
00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:53.760
His team identified epigenetic downregulation of HLA class II

49
00:02:53.800 --> 00:02:57.760
molecules on AML blasts as a mechanism of immune escape,

50
00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:01.840
leading to post-transplant relapse, work that has reshaped the field's

51
00:03:01.880 --> 00:03:05.280
understanding of AML recurrence after chemotherapy or

52
00:03:05.400 --> 00:03:06.660
allogeneic transplant.

53
00:03:07.580 --> 00:03:11.340
In recent years, Dr. DiPersio and his team have focused on developing innovative

54
00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:15.420
CAR T-cell therapies and bispecific antibodies targeting a number

55
00:03:15.490 --> 00:03:18.900
of malignancies by leveraging genetic and expression

56
00:03:18.940 --> 00:03:22.320
profiling of primary patient tumor samples to identify

57
00:03:22.360 --> 00:03:24.440
novel, actionable protein targets.

58
00:03:25.560 --> 00:03:28.960
Dr. DiPersio's scientific leadership has earned him numerous honors,

59
00:03:29.060 --> 00:03:32.210
including the AACR Joseph H. Burkeniel Memorial

60
00:03:32.280 --> 00:03:35.620
Award for Outstanding Achievement in Clinical Cancer Research,

61
00:03:36.160 --> 00:03:40.090
the ASH Mentor Award for Clinical Investigation, the Giants of

62
00:03:40.180 --> 00:03:42.480
Cancer Award for Leukemia, an

63
00:03:42.580 --> 00:03:46.280
NCI R35 Outstanding Investigator

64
00:03:46.340 --> 00:03:50.079
Award, and the Harriet P. Dustin Award for Science

65
00:03:50.500 --> 00:03:53.060
from the American College of Physicians, among others.

66
00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:57.520
A dedicated member of AACR since 2009, Dr.

67
00:03:57.760 --> 00:04:01.200
DiPersio has been a tireless champion for patient-centered research,

68
00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:05.420
personally enrolling more than 1,700 patients in therapeutic

69
00:04:05.460 --> 00:04:06.000
trials.

70
00:04:07.280 --> 00:04:11.020
It is my great honor and privilege to introduce the 2026

71
00:04:11.060 --> 00:04:14.920
recipient of this AACR Award for Outstanding Achievement in Blood

72
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.620
Cancer Research, Dr. John DiPersio. Thank you.

73
00:04:25.680 --> 00:04:29.000
Okay. Well, thank you so much for that kind

74
00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:30.640
introduction, Dr. Stegmaier.

75
00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:35.500
I don't know what to say, really. When I got the email

76
00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:36.480
from AACR,

77
00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:38.000
I

78
00:04:38.820 --> 00:04:41.400
turned to one of my colleagues who was sitting next to me,

79
00:04:42.420 --> 00:04:43.960
and I said, "Is this a joke?"

80
00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:46.100
This is

81
00:04:46.920 --> 00:04:50.740
amazing. I can use a whole slew of words,

82
00:04:50.840 --> 00:04:53.540
but I was just shocked. I guess that's the best word.

83
00:04:54.460 --> 00:04:58.120
But the most important thing is that I felt like maybe it

84
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:02.440
really provided some

85
00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:04.640
specific

86
00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:09.469
acknowledgement for all the people I worked with over the years, my

87
00:05:09.600 --> 00:05:11.160
colleagues, my trainees,

88
00:05:12.060 --> 00:05:15.930
my mentors. I'll spend a minute or two at the end to tell you who I'm

89
00:05:15.960 --> 00:05:17.370
going to thank for this award, but

90
00:05:18.520 --> 00:05:20.460
they deserve much of the credit.

91
00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:25.000
They've done all of the hard work, and I get to stand up here and

92
00:05:25.880 --> 00:05:29.360
give the talk. So to them, I

93
00:05:31.220 --> 00:05:35.040
thank. And to AACR, I'd like to thank as well for

94
00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:37.960
this incredible honor. I'm so humbled.

95
00:05:38.020 --> 00:05:39.020
Now,

96
00:05:40.100 --> 00:05:44.060
these are my

97
00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:47.730
disclosures. I want to talk about something that

98
00:05:47.840 --> 00:05:48.900
has been a recent

99
00:05:50.300 --> 00:05:54.060
focus of my lab, and that is focusing on T cell malignancies.

100
00:05:54.510 --> 00:05:57.660
And I'm going to talk about developing reagents to treat T cell

101
00:05:57.700 --> 00:06:00.508
malignancies, specifically T cell-...

102
00:06:00.528 --> 00:06:02.268
well in T-cell non-Hodgkin's lymphoma,

103
00:06:03.168 --> 00:06:04.008
and secondly,

104
00:06:04.928 --> 00:06:08.808
to give you a little hint about how you might actually enhance

105
00:06:09.088 --> 00:06:11.848
the activity of these reagents in a very simple way.

106
00:06:12.528 --> 00:06:16.388
And then also, since immunotherapies are associated with

107
00:06:16.448 --> 00:06:20.318
some toxicities, how we might try to understand the biology

108
00:06:20.368 --> 00:06:23.488
of some of these toxicities and intervene and mitigate them.

109
00:06:24.908 --> 00:06:28.818
So T-cell ALL, unlike B-cell

110
00:06:28.868 --> 00:06:31.708
malignancies, has been poorly investigated.

111
00:06:32.708 --> 00:06:34.288
And here's a

112
00:06:35.728 --> 00:06:39.548
data from the MRC and the ECOG looking at outcomes of patients with

113
00:06:39.588 --> 00:06:43.418
T-cell ALL. And you can see that adults with T-cell ALL,

114
00:06:43.508 --> 00:06:47.418
their chance of long-term survival is around 30%, and

115
00:06:47.468 --> 00:06:51.328
if you relapse with T-cell ALL, your chance of survival at one year is

116
00:06:51.368 --> 00:06:55.108
only 24% and 11% at six years.

117
00:06:55.208 --> 00:06:58.688
Children fare not much better. In fact, children,

118
00:06:59.168 --> 00:07:02.998
they have a horrible disease. And for adults and

119
00:07:03.108 --> 00:07:07.068
children with relapsed T-cell ALL, there really are no

120
00:07:07.168 --> 00:07:10.648
alternatives. There's one drug approved called nilotinib,

121
00:07:11.188 --> 00:07:14.888
and the complete response rates for nilotinib are only 11%,

122
00:07:15.348 --> 00:07:18.088
and the median time to progression is only three months.

123
00:07:18.628 --> 00:07:22.368
So there really is no option for patients that relapse, and that's what we'd like

124
00:07:22.408 --> 00:07:26.108
to pursue. These are some of the risk factors associated with T-cell ALL.

125
00:07:27.448 --> 00:07:27.848
Well,

126
00:07:29.348 --> 00:07:30.928
these are some of the targets that

127
00:07:32.528 --> 00:07:36.288
one might go after if you were looking at immunotherapy for T-cell ALL, and the

128
00:07:36.308 --> 00:07:39.148
best targets here are CD2, CD7,

129
00:07:40.088 --> 00:07:43.518
and CD5. And so we decided to pursue the most

130
00:07:43.648 --> 00:07:47.078
highly and universally expressed target in T-cell ALL, and that's

131
00:07:47.108 --> 00:07:49.838
CD7, as a target for immunotherapy.

132
00:07:50.878 --> 00:07:54.728
And so the challenge, though, and a challenge that was taken up by a

133
00:07:54.768 --> 00:07:58.688
great postdoc in my lab who's now left to be the chief scientific

134
00:07:58.848 --> 00:08:02.748
officer of WuJin, a company that was really born

135
00:08:02.788 --> 00:08:03.688
from this effort.

136
00:08:05.008 --> 00:08:08.888
The challenges are that the target antigens that you would go

137
00:08:09.048 --> 00:08:12.908
after in the T-cell ALL is shared in the effector

138
00:08:12.948 --> 00:08:16.598
T cell, resulting in fratricide. And harvesting

139
00:08:16.668 --> 00:08:20.248
adequate numbers of T cells deficient in tumor cells

140
00:08:20.748 --> 00:08:24.568
is really almost impossible because these patients have leukemia,

141
00:08:24.628 --> 00:08:28.328
and any genetic manipulation of T cells obtained in peripheral

142
00:08:28.368 --> 00:08:32.288
blood would also potentially genetically manipulate malignant cells and making them

143
00:08:32.348 --> 00:08:33.428
potentially resistant

144
00:08:34.768 --> 00:08:38.749
to any immunotherapy. Well, one could use T cells from someone else,

145
00:08:38.828 --> 00:08:42.028
but that's associated with life-threatening graft versus host disease,

146
00:08:42.489 --> 00:08:44.748
especially in these immunosuppressed recipients.

147
00:08:44.808 --> 00:08:48.688
So we thought, could we change the paradigm and provide,

148
00:08:49.108 --> 00:08:52.848
for the first time, some immunotherapeutic approach

149
00:08:53.028 --> 00:08:56.808
for patients with T-cell ALL using

150
00:08:57.188 --> 00:09:01.138
gene therapy by gene editing the CAR T to delete the

151
00:09:01.168 --> 00:09:04.898
target antigen, in this case, initially, it's CD7.

152
00:09:05.708 --> 00:09:09.417
And then also the T cell receptor alpha subunit, which is absolutely

153
00:09:09.448 --> 00:09:13.428
essential for trafficking of the T cell receptor to the surface and for

154
00:09:13.468 --> 00:09:17.108
the ability of an effector T cell to recognize self from non-self.

155
00:09:17.708 --> 00:09:21.688
And so this is just something that we worked on for a while, and we developed

156
00:09:21.708 --> 00:09:25.488
a highly efficient multiplex platform for

157
00:09:25.628 --> 00:09:29.537
deleting both of these targets while also transducing

158
00:09:29.537 --> 00:09:33.428
a CAR, which was a high-affinity binder that we

159
00:09:33.528 --> 00:09:36.588
had screened for as well. This is just a

160
00:09:37.648 --> 00:09:40.868
diagram of the manufacturing of

161
00:09:40.948 --> 00:09:44.928
these clinical-grade CAR-Ts now, where the donor T

162
00:09:45.048 --> 00:09:48.908
cells from an allogeneic donor are genetically

163
00:09:48.968 --> 00:09:52.828
modified to delete both CD7 and T cell receptor alpha

164
00:09:52.868 --> 00:09:56.268
subunit. And then they're transduced with a

165
00:09:56.308 --> 00:09:59.868
lentivirus expressing CD7 CAR

166
00:09:59.968 --> 00:10:02.868
under the control of a 4BB endodomain.

167
00:10:03.708 --> 00:10:04.168
And then

168
00:10:06.028 --> 00:10:09.548
these cells are then subjected to one round

169
00:10:09.728 --> 00:10:13.408
of alpha/beta depletion since the efficiency of

170
00:10:14.388 --> 00:10:18.048
TCR depletion is not 100%, and there's sufficient numbers of

171
00:10:18.128 --> 00:10:19.748
alpha/beta T cells that

172
00:10:21.408 --> 00:10:25.118
are present at the end of this procedure to kill any recipient if you're

173
00:10:25.168 --> 00:10:27.268
using mismatched allodonors.

174
00:10:28.698 --> 00:10:32.028
So this is the result. I'll skip ahead six years.

175
00:10:32.588 --> 00:10:36.578
So we worked on this, worked on it, helped develop this, and we had

176
00:10:36.588 --> 00:10:40.418
to make a decision whether we would try to do this ourselves and

177
00:10:40.428 --> 00:10:44.388
try to make something for patients for which there was no therapies at the time,

178
00:10:44.948 --> 00:10:48.868
or whether we would just make this discovery and move on to another topic

179
00:10:48.908 --> 00:10:51.848
and get another R01 on something different.

180
00:10:52.428 --> 00:10:56.008
And so we thought that after seeing a few patients with T-cell ALL

181
00:10:56.108 --> 00:11:00.008
die from no option, we thought that maybe we should try to push this

182
00:11:00.068 --> 00:11:04.048
forward. So we played a major part in developing this reagent,

183
00:11:04.088 --> 00:11:08.048
and this is the first Phase I study here that was just published in "Blood."

184
00:11:08.108 --> 00:11:10.248
Armin Gabati, a colleague of mine, was the PI.

185
00:11:10.748 --> 00:11:14.448
And in the recommended Phase II dose for the CAR T, there was an

186
00:11:14.568 --> 00:11:18.488
82% CR rate, which has certainly dramatically changed the

187
00:11:18.548 --> 00:11:20.308
paradigm of outcome in these patients.

188
00:11:20.968 --> 00:11:24.748
The first patients at the recommended Phase II dose is shown in the upper

189
00:11:24.808 --> 00:11:28.008
right corner, showing a complete metabolic response.

190
00:11:29.168 --> 00:11:29.608
This

191
00:11:30.488 --> 00:11:34.108
was recently published, and the FDA said they were impressed

192
00:11:34.148 --> 00:11:37.188
enough that they said proceed with the registration study.

193
00:11:37.268 --> 00:11:40.548
So this is the design of the registration study, which is a much

194
00:11:40.968 --> 00:11:44.428
larger, multi-institutional, multinational trial.

195
00:11:44.868 --> 00:11:48.828
It's actually 10 institutions from multiple countries around the

196
00:11:48.897 --> 00:11:49.188
world,

197
00:11:50.048 --> 00:11:53.508
and there's going to be about 120 patients in this trial.

198
00:11:53.568 --> 00:11:57.467
It's about halfway done now. Hopefully, we'll see the results in the

199
00:11:57.508 --> 00:12:01.448
next 18 months.So we have

200
00:12:01.458 --> 00:12:05.008
already treated enough patients to know that some patients do

201
00:12:05.048 --> 00:12:05.668
relapse.

202
00:12:06.848 --> 00:12:10.608
It's not clear if they relapse or we don't completely clear their disease, so

203
00:12:10.648 --> 00:12:14.388
there's more work to be done. The other issue is, of course, when you're

204
00:12:14.398 --> 00:12:18.288
targeting a CD7, you're getting rid of normal NK cells and T cells, and

205
00:12:18.368 --> 00:12:21.828
so you're left with an immunodeficient patient, and so infections are

206
00:12:21.948 --> 00:12:24.868
problematic as well. And so the question is how to

207
00:12:26.628 --> 00:12:30.568
sandwich this in all of the therapies that these patients get so that you

208
00:12:30.608 --> 00:12:31.008
don't

209
00:12:32.368 --> 00:12:36.268
have a dead patient from some infection or some other complication.

210
00:12:36.788 --> 00:12:40.408
And so we noticed that some of the patients had lost

211
00:12:40.488 --> 00:12:44.308
CD7 expression. In fact, most of them that relapsed had lost

212
00:12:44.348 --> 00:12:48.128
CD7 expression. And so we thought that it would be reasonable

213
00:12:48.388 --> 00:12:51.508
for the ones who relapsed to consider an alternative treatment.

214
00:12:52.108 --> 00:12:55.988
In addition, we also noted that there was really no good treatments

215
00:12:56.048 --> 00:12:59.648
for T cell malignancies either. These are non-Hodgkin's lymphomas

216
00:13:00.028 --> 00:13:03.288
and certainly patients that relapse with non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.

217
00:13:03.318 --> 00:13:05.868
And this is a heat map on the left showing

218
00:13:07.428 --> 00:13:10.868
the expression of CD2 in all the different T cell lymphomas.

219
00:13:10.908 --> 00:13:14.418
You can see that probably more than any other target, it's

220
00:13:14.768 --> 00:13:18.648
overexpressed in all of these, even more so than CD7

221
00:13:18.668 --> 00:13:19.608
or CD5.

222
00:13:20.668 --> 00:13:24.498
So this is a very good target for exploitation, and it's

223
00:13:24.568 --> 00:13:28.238
also a good target for treating T cell non-Hodgkin's lymphomas,

224
00:13:28.308 --> 00:13:32.268
especially those that relapse. This is just an example of outcomes

225
00:13:32.308 --> 00:13:33.027
of patients with

226
00:13:34.908 --> 00:13:36.948
newly diagnosed peripheral T cell lymphoma.

227
00:13:37.548 --> 00:13:41.308
And you can see that the outcomes for all peripheral T cell lymphomas

228
00:13:41.348 --> 00:13:45.088
is really quite poor. Those patients in that really

229
00:13:45.148 --> 00:13:48.468
lower category here that relapse are really doomed.

230
00:13:49.008 --> 00:13:50.668
And these are the only patients that do well.

231
00:13:50.708 --> 00:13:52.568
These are the ALK-positive

232
00:13:54.888 --> 00:13:58.168
T cell lymphomas that seem to do well with modern therapy, including

233
00:13:59.748 --> 00:14:02.428
those therapies that include transplant and

234
00:14:04.468 --> 00:14:06.088
CD30-targeted therapies.

235
00:14:07.548 --> 00:14:11.228
So we decided to do the same thing with CD2 to make a

236
00:14:11.288 --> 00:14:14.368
CD2 targeted approach. Same idea.

237
00:14:14.488 --> 00:14:18.428
We knocked out the TRAC locus, and we knocked

238
00:14:18.448 --> 00:14:22.328
out the CD2 locus. We put in a CD2 CAR

239
00:14:22.468 --> 00:14:26.428
to CD2, and we tested it against three different CD2 positive

240
00:14:26.508 --> 00:14:27.098
cell lines.

241
00:14:27.968 --> 00:14:31.908
And you can see the red line that there was very effective

242
00:14:31.968 --> 00:14:34.888
in vitro killing of all three cell lines.

243
00:14:36.088 --> 00:14:39.388
What we didn't expect was what we saw in the next slide, and that is we did a

244
00:14:39.468 --> 00:14:43.228
simple experiment where we deleted CD2 in a CAR

245
00:14:43.508 --> 00:14:46.948
and made the CAR to CD19 as a sort of a control.

246
00:14:47.488 --> 00:14:50.788
And we tested the role of wild type UCAR19.

247
00:14:50.908 --> 00:14:54.588
These are universal CARs to CD19 that

248
00:14:54.668 --> 00:14:54.988
had

249
00:14:55.828 --> 00:14:57.368
the CD2 locus

250
00:14:58.948 --> 00:15:02.888
intact or the CD2 locus deleted. And what

251
00:15:02.928 --> 00:15:06.768
we found is that when you delete CD2 in T cells and in these

252
00:15:06.788 --> 00:15:10.728
CAR T cells, they take a huge hit. We did not see that with

253
00:15:10.768 --> 00:15:14.408
CD7. When we knocked out CD7, the CD7 deleted T

254
00:15:14.508 --> 00:15:16.608
cells functioned completely normally.

255
00:15:16.648 --> 00:15:20.548
So we could delete CD7, thus the background for

256
00:15:20.628 --> 00:15:20.768
the

257
00:15:23.048 --> 00:15:26.928
Wu CAR007 study. Now, the question

258
00:15:27.008 --> 00:15:30.708
is, how are we going to fix this? So is there a way that we can get

259
00:15:30.768 --> 00:15:34.088
this loss of CD2 back

260
00:15:34.668 --> 00:15:38.648
in these CAR T cells? And so we

261
00:15:39.148 --> 00:15:43.108
started looking at the biology of CD2, and sure enough, CD2

262
00:15:43.148 --> 00:15:47.088
has a very critical function as a positive costimulatory

263
00:15:47.148 --> 00:15:50.888
molecule for T cells. It binds a molecule called

264
00:15:50.948 --> 00:15:54.448
CD58 and CD48 in the mouse,

265
00:15:55.008 --> 00:15:58.168
and that this provides a positive costimulation which provides

266
00:15:58.268 --> 00:16:02.248
competency to T cells. And so with

267
00:16:02.328 --> 00:16:02.688
that

268
00:16:03.508 --> 00:16:07.118
CD2 gone, these T cells are markedly hampered and

269
00:16:07.268 --> 00:16:11.088
ineffective. They work fine in vitro, but they don't work at all in

270
00:16:11.148 --> 00:16:14.768
vivo. And so what we decided to do is take the lead

271
00:16:15.528 --> 00:16:19.128
of these three investigating groups that had developed ways of

272
00:16:19.147 --> 00:16:22.708
epitope masking CD45 and other molecules

273
00:16:23.208 --> 00:16:27.028
as a way of sort of disguising the endogenous CD2

274
00:16:27.128 --> 00:16:29.848
so that it's invisible to our CAR to CD2.

275
00:16:30.348 --> 00:16:34.268
And at the same time, we looked back in the literature, and sure enough, there

276
00:16:34.308 --> 00:16:38.188
was an antibody being developed called ciplizumab,

277
00:16:38.608 --> 00:16:39.388
which binds

278
00:16:40.888 --> 00:16:44.788
to the human CD2 very well but does not bind

279
00:16:44.828 --> 00:16:48.488
to the baboon CD2. And the baboon CD2

280
00:16:48.568 --> 00:16:51.968
differs from the human CD2 by only three amino acids.

281
00:16:52.508 --> 00:16:56.488
And so to make a long story short, we mutated those three

282
00:16:56.548 --> 00:16:59.968
amino acids in every combination you can imagine and

283
00:17:00.028 --> 00:17:03.718
finally came to the conclusion that if we mutated two of these

284
00:17:03.768 --> 00:17:07.709
amino acids by CRISPR, then that CD2

285
00:17:07.768 --> 00:17:11.748
was expressed on the surface of cells and bound

286
00:17:11.828 --> 00:17:14.048
to CD58 completely normally.

287
00:17:15.168 --> 00:17:19.048
And then also when we made those CD2

288
00:17:19.408 --> 00:17:23.268
positive cells that the ciplizumab antibody could not see because they

289
00:17:23.288 --> 00:17:25.108
could only see the

290
00:17:26.648 --> 00:17:30.568
wild type CD2 and we had converted the endogenous CD2

291
00:17:30.628 --> 00:17:33.428
into a baboon CD2, which was invisible to the CAR.

292
00:17:34.068 --> 00:17:37.608
And the CAR was made from the ScFv from the ciplizumab

293
00:17:37.628 --> 00:17:41.268
antibody. So this is how we were pursuing this epitope masking

294
00:17:41.328 --> 00:17:43.648
approach. And we expressed the CAR

295
00:17:44.488 --> 00:17:47.668
in these cells as well, and they function

296
00:17:48.208 --> 00:17:52.058
perfectly well.So we wanted to

297
00:17:52.098 --> 00:17:55.258
know how they functioned in vitro and in vivo.

298
00:17:55.318 --> 00:17:58.838
So in vitro, what we did is we tested the knockout CAR Ts

299
00:17:59.898 --> 00:18:03.838
to CD2 and the edited CAR Ts to CD2 in a

300
00:18:03.878 --> 00:18:04.898
repetitive tumor

301
00:18:05.978 --> 00:18:09.958
culture assay where we add tumor to the CARs every two or

302
00:18:10.018 --> 00:18:11.838
three days, let the CARs kill the tumor.

303
00:18:12.278 --> 00:18:16.258
The CARs would divide, kill the tumor, and eventually they get

304
00:18:16.298 --> 00:18:20.248
exhausted. So this is a way of looking at persistence and exhaustion

305
00:18:20.618 --> 00:18:24.018
using this in vitro tumor replating assay that many laboratories

306
00:18:24.498 --> 00:18:27.978
use around the world today. And so this is what we found.

307
00:18:28.858 --> 00:18:32.318
When we compare the knockout, which is the black line here, to

308
00:18:32.358 --> 00:18:33.377
the edited

309
00:18:34.318 --> 00:18:38.268
CAR Ts, there's a dramatic difference in the expansion of those CAR T's.

310
00:18:38.298 --> 00:18:41.218
So our edited CAR T's really were

311
00:18:41.298 --> 00:18:45.198
outperforming the knockout CAR T's by huge amounts.

312
00:18:45.678 --> 00:18:49.658
And then also, this is a slightly different assay, but you can see with repetitive

313
00:18:49.718 --> 00:18:53.518
stimulation, the knockout CAR T's sort of

314
00:18:53.618 --> 00:18:57.498
die after the fourth round of stimulation, while

315
00:18:57.578 --> 00:19:01.018
the edited CAR T's can extend out to 13 rounds of

316
00:19:01.058 --> 00:19:04.937
re-stimulation, in which tumor cells are given every three days.

317
00:19:07.578 --> 00:19:11.318
And we also tested at each round of stimulation that the

318
00:19:11.398 --> 00:19:15.278
function of the CAR T's, and you can see by about the sixth or

319
00:19:15.378 --> 00:19:18.618
seventh round of re-stimulation, you can see that there's

320
00:19:19.138 --> 00:19:23.098
starting to be a difference between the function of the knockout CAR T's

321
00:19:23.158 --> 00:19:26.898
versus the edited CAR T's. So that by the time you get to around

322
00:19:26.938 --> 00:19:30.498
10 or 11, the edited CAR T's look completely

323
00:19:30.538 --> 00:19:34.358
functional and the knockout CAR T's are completely

324
00:19:34.418 --> 00:19:37.978
exhausted. Next, this is the definition of exhaustion.

325
00:19:38.988 --> 00:19:41.318
They can't actually kill the targets,

326
00:19:42.518 --> 00:19:43.878
and they can't generate

327
00:19:45.398 --> 00:19:46.238
interferon gamma.

328
00:19:47.818 --> 00:19:48.428
So this is

329
00:19:49.638 --> 00:19:52.998
one other thing that we didn't expect to see, but with repetitive

330
00:19:53.078 --> 00:19:55.538
stimulation, you can see that here are the

331
00:19:56.818 --> 00:20:00.718
knockout CAR T's down here in the dark, and here are the fours

332
00:20:00.738 --> 00:20:04.278
and eights of the edited CAR T's. They expand

333
00:20:04.318 --> 00:20:07.798
dramatically. And also the persistence of

334
00:20:08.798 --> 00:20:12.698
as these cells get more and more exhausted from the knockout, there's more

335
00:20:12.718 --> 00:20:16.218
and more eights. And you can see in the edited population,

336
00:20:16.278 --> 00:20:19.898
the fours are well-preserved until the very end.

337
00:20:20.338 --> 00:20:24.238
So this preserves CD4 function, which we think may be

338
00:20:24.278 --> 00:20:27.478
important for overall CAR T-cell efficacy.

339
00:20:30.018 --> 00:20:33.878
And then the final experiment, we tested this in an in vivo experiment,

340
00:20:33.958 --> 00:20:34.458
and this

341
00:20:36.718 --> 00:20:40.438
is the results in which we put in the knockout.

342
00:20:41.138 --> 00:20:44.958
You can see that the knockout cells, really, this is the tumor

343
00:20:45.038 --> 00:20:48.698
only. This is the knockout, and here are the edited cells, and all the

344
00:20:48.778 --> 00:20:52.018
animals survive, and they control the tumor quite well.

345
00:20:52.838 --> 00:20:56.778
So this is what we'd like to take forward into the clinic for patients who

346
00:20:56.818 --> 00:21:00.358
have relapses after CD7 therapy and also for

347
00:21:00.398 --> 00:21:04.058
non-Hodgkin's lymphomas that require CAR T-cell therapy

348
00:21:04.258 --> 00:21:06.878
for relapse or refractory disease.

349
00:21:07.838 --> 00:21:11.378
So the final thing is that since the CD2 is very essential,

350
00:21:11.918 --> 00:21:14.498
what Jerry Zhang did, who has really been

351
00:21:15.358 --> 00:21:19.238
leading this work in the lab, he decided to actually take the

352
00:21:19.258 --> 00:21:23.218
cytoplasmic domain of CD2 and incorporate it into

353
00:21:23.278 --> 00:21:25.558
the CAR itself. And so

354
00:21:26.478 --> 00:21:30.438
what you can see is that there's a little bit of activity with

355
00:21:30.458 --> 00:21:34.038
the CD28 alone, but all of the others that lack

356
00:21:34.558 --> 00:21:38.198
the intact CD2 have very poor CAR

357
00:21:38.238 --> 00:21:40.318
T-cell expansion. However,

358
00:21:40.818 --> 00:21:43.898
when you look at the

359
00:21:45.358 --> 00:21:45.758
one

360
00:21:47.478 --> 00:21:51.398
construct here in which he's inserted a part of

361
00:21:51.458 --> 00:21:55.138
the cytoplasmic domain of CD2, which is conserved

362
00:21:55.178 --> 00:21:58.538
between many species and obviously we think is very important for

363
00:21:58.558 --> 00:22:02.418
signaling, if we put that in the middle of the CAR, then these cells

364
00:22:02.438 --> 00:22:05.687
dramatically improve in their expansion and

365
00:22:05.997 --> 00:22:09.627
anti-tumor efficacy. And this is another way of actually getting

366
00:22:09.627 --> 00:22:13.578
around actually having to express an epitope-matched

367
00:22:13.618 --> 00:22:16.438
CD2 in these CAR T cells.

368
00:22:18.218 --> 00:22:21.898
So we've gone on, and we've done some manufacturing,

369
00:22:22.158 --> 00:22:25.938
and we've manufactured UCAR T2

370
00:22:26.018 --> 00:22:29.978
in large scale using gREX. And the way

371
00:22:30.058 --> 00:22:32.578
we had to do it, we had a few little tricks here.

372
00:22:32.638 --> 00:22:36.418
The first little trick was we had to incorporate dasatinib during the

373
00:22:36.458 --> 00:22:40.258
early phases of the expansion and transduction because of

374
00:22:40.378 --> 00:22:43.778
early fratricide. So when we tried to, even

375
00:22:44.338 --> 00:22:44.778
with our

376
00:22:46.298 --> 00:22:50.218
novel approaches, if we didn't add dasatinib early on, we saw

377
00:22:50.378 --> 00:22:53.998
a lot of fratricide early on. And when we added dasatinib, we had

378
00:22:54.078 --> 00:22:57.507
marked improvement in expansion and viability of the cells.

379
00:22:58.058 --> 00:23:01.878
And at the end of the expansion, we have enough cells to

380
00:23:01.958 --> 00:23:05.758
treat between 50 and 100 patients, and we wanted to

381
00:23:05.818 --> 00:23:08.278
know what those cells looked like.

382
00:23:08.858 --> 00:23:12.518
And here's an example of the cells that have been expanded.

383
00:23:12.548 --> 00:23:16.338
And you can see that there's still 5% or 6%

384
00:23:17.538 --> 00:23:20.658
of these TRAK positive cells. And this is enough to kill a recipient.

385
00:23:21.078 --> 00:23:24.898
So we have to get rid of them. And to get rid of them, we have to either run them

386
00:23:24.998 --> 00:23:28.958
over an alpha/beta affinity column or get rid of them

387
00:23:29.018 --> 00:23:31.638
some other way. And so there is now a

388
00:23:31.738 --> 00:23:33.138
GMP-approved

389
00:23:34.098 --> 00:23:37.838
OKT3 antibody that you can just throw into the

390
00:23:37.898 --> 00:23:41.658
mix and without actually doing any purification, and it

391
00:23:41.718 --> 00:23:45.518
induces activation-induced cell death for any residual alpha/beta

392
00:23:45.598 --> 00:23:49.458
positive cells that are left. And you can see how nice and clean the product is,

393
00:23:50.038 --> 00:23:51.998
negating the need to do

394
00:23:52.898 --> 00:23:56.818
ex vivo purification with alpha/beta columns, which will

395
00:23:56.918 --> 00:24:00.888
save at least half the product.And we tested these

396
00:24:01.168 --> 00:24:04.268
in vitro, and they're highly effective at killing targets.

397
00:24:05.528 --> 00:24:07.048
So what

398
00:24:08.268 --> 00:24:12.248
is another problem with this? So, the first problem

399
00:24:12.308 --> 00:24:16.128
is immunosuppression because you're targeting CD7 and CD2 on normal

400
00:24:16.228 --> 00:24:17.708
T cells and NK cells.

401
00:24:18.588 --> 00:24:22.118
And this has been an issue, and we still need to work on this.

402
00:24:23.028 --> 00:24:26.428
It's not an easy problem to solve, unless you find

403
00:24:26.488 --> 00:24:30.348
targets that are only expressed on the malignant T cells,

404
00:24:30.368 --> 00:24:34.348
but not on normal T cells. And so we did a genome-wide and proteomics-wide

405
00:24:34.468 --> 00:24:38.308
screen of a number of T cell ALLs, and we have a number of

406
00:24:38.388 --> 00:24:41.928
candidate genes that are universally not

407
00:24:41.968 --> 00:24:45.288
expressed on normal T cells, but expressed on malignant T cells.

408
00:24:45.328 --> 00:24:47.048
This is just one of them. This

409
00:24:48.688 --> 00:24:51.548
came up for a screen for AML, believe it or not.

410
00:24:52.108 --> 00:24:55.688
It's called CDU305, which is also called LAIR1.

411
00:24:56.328 --> 00:25:00.248
And LAIR1 is specifically expressed at high levels and uniformly

412
00:25:00.328 --> 00:25:03.588
on all T cell ALL cells and not on T cells.

413
00:25:04.008 --> 00:25:07.388
So we think that we could even develop in the future a targeting approach,

414
00:25:07.928 --> 00:25:11.838
targeting LAIR1 or CD305, which would kill the malignant cells but

415
00:25:11.908 --> 00:25:12.648
not

416
00:25:13.528 --> 00:25:16.188
deplete the normal T cells or NK cells.

417
00:25:16.888 --> 00:25:20.548
And another approach was pursued by

418
00:25:20.588 --> 00:25:24.388
Miriam Kim in the lab before she went out and started her own lab.

419
00:25:25.148 --> 00:25:28.488
And this is just deleting the target in the

420
00:25:28.528 --> 00:25:30.628
hematopoietic stem cells. This is tricky.

421
00:25:31.088 --> 00:25:33.248
It's very complicated, very expensive.

422
00:25:33.608 --> 00:25:37.488
You're modifying hematopoietic stem cells with gene editing, so there's a

423
00:25:37.548 --> 00:25:38.858
lot more introspection,

424
00:25:39.728 --> 00:25:42.968
a lot more oversight, and also lots of more

425
00:25:43.508 --> 00:25:46.428
issues relating to CD2 versus CD7.

426
00:25:46.888 --> 00:25:49.628
But in this case, you can see how well it worked in the mouse.

427
00:25:50.128 --> 00:25:54.018
She transplanted wild type hematopoietic stem cells,

428
00:25:54.108 --> 00:25:57.948
human hematopoietic stem cells into an NSGS mouse and got them to

429
00:25:57.988 --> 00:26:01.248
engraft, and then treated those mice with a CAR to

430
00:26:01.308 --> 00:26:05.008
CD7. And you can see that all of the CD3

431
00:26:05.068 --> 00:26:08.927
positive cells disappeared because all of those cells express CD7.

432
00:26:09.427 --> 00:26:13.328
When she did the transplant with stem cells that lack CD7, she did the

433
00:26:13.368 --> 00:26:17.068
same thing, and she found that there was no decrease in the T cell

434
00:26:17.088 --> 00:26:20.918
population, and she was able to eliminate any potential

435
00:26:20.948 --> 00:26:24.578
contaminating malignant cells. So this is another way of getting

436
00:26:24.628 --> 00:26:28.408
around it, but as I said, it's quite complicated and

437
00:26:28.448 --> 00:26:28.988
difficult.

438
00:26:30.288 --> 00:26:33.048
So what about enhancing CAR T cell function?

439
00:26:33.248 --> 00:26:37.148
So there are many ways that you might be able to increase

440
00:26:37.188 --> 00:26:40.468
CAR T cell function, and there's lots of genes that have been

441
00:26:40.568 --> 00:26:44.008
overexpressed, that have been deleted, that have been modified.

442
00:26:44.388 --> 00:26:47.968
These are complicated. They're gene therapy, they're gene editing, and so

443
00:26:48.828 --> 00:26:52.768
expensive as well. And so we thought that just adding a cytokine, could

444
00:26:52.808 --> 00:26:55.758
we add just a cytokine to enhance CAR T cell function?

445
00:26:56.188 --> 00:27:00.028
This is an example of a long-acting cytokine called

446
00:27:00.228 --> 00:27:03.968
IL-7 or NTi-7, which is a fusion of a genetically

447
00:27:04.048 --> 00:27:07.828
modified IL-7 linked to the IgD and IgG

448
00:27:07.968 --> 00:27:08.848
Fc domains.

449
00:27:09.828 --> 00:27:10.948
And you can see this is a large

450
00:27:11.848 --> 00:27:15.708
molecule. Instead of having to be given every day or every other day

451
00:27:15.808 --> 00:27:19.488
like recombinant IL-7, this only has to be given every two to three

452
00:27:19.568 --> 00:27:23.368
weeks, and it enhances CAR T cell expansion in vivo.

453
00:27:24.108 --> 00:27:27.908
And it also enhances the tumor replating efficiency of

454
00:27:27.948 --> 00:27:31.888
CAR T cells. And so we said, "Okay, will

455
00:27:31.928 --> 00:27:35.068
it work in vivo?" And so this is an example in a T

456
00:27:35.228 --> 00:27:37.468
cell non-Hodgkin's lymphoma model.

457
00:27:37.588 --> 00:27:39.188
So we inject these

458
00:27:40.548 --> 00:27:44.098
bioluminescently labeled malignant T cells into these mice,

459
00:27:44.528 --> 00:27:48.488
and you can see that the red dotted line of the total

460
00:27:48.568 --> 00:27:50.398
photons increases as expected,

461
00:27:51.428 --> 00:27:53.688
and the mice die of progressive disease.

462
00:27:54.288 --> 00:27:57.588
And the mice that get the universal CAR T to CD2,

463
00:27:58.348 --> 00:28:02.068
these are all experiments that are much easier to do with the universal

464
00:28:02.108 --> 00:28:05.668
CAR than a regular CAR because there's no confounding issues of graft versus host

465
00:28:05.728 --> 00:28:06.128
disease.

466
00:28:07.028 --> 00:28:10.428
And you can see that these animals had a profound improvement

467
00:28:11.308 --> 00:28:15.008
in tumor clearance, but they all eventually died and succumbed to their

468
00:28:15.048 --> 00:28:18.608
disease. And here on the dotted line are the same

469
00:28:19.568 --> 00:28:23.448
CAR T cells injected into these mice just with several doses

470
00:28:23.508 --> 00:28:27.468
of interleukin-7. You can see that all the animals are cured, and

471
00:28:27.488 --> 00:28:31.248
they have no evidence of disease. So in this T cell non-Hodgkin's

472
00:28:31.268 --> 00:28:34.828
lymphoma model, the addition of just a cytokine, IL-7,

473
00:28:35.328 --> 00:28:39.248
provided curative potential. And this is a B cell

474
00:28:39.288 --> 00:28:42.208
model. This is a Ramos B cell model. Same idea.

475
00:28:42.628 --> 00:28:45.648
Injected the tumor cells and then treated them with either nothing.

476
00:28:45.988 --> 00:28:49.868
And we did this in a stress dose so that the CAR T cells had a limited

477
00:28:49.908 --> 00:28:53.708
effect. And then we added a couple of doses of IL-7, and

478
00:28:53.808 --> 00:28:57.028
all the mice survive. And there's a 10,000

479
00:28:57.988 --> 00:29:01.628
to 100,000-fold difference in the expansion of CAR T

480
00:29:01.748 --> 00:29:02.158
cells

481
00:29:03.888 --> 00:29:07.748
in these mice. And you can see that the CAR T

482
00:29:07.828 --> 00:29:11.708
cells markedly expand as well. So it works in a T cell model,

483
00:29:11.828 --> 00:29:14.488
B cell model. And this is an AML model.

484
00:29:14.568 --> 00:29:18.408
This is a UCART to CD33. Same idea, limiting

485
00:29:18.508 --> 00:29:22.428
dose of CAR Ts. You can see that provides some benefit to

486
00:29:22.468 --> 00:29:26.448
these animals and some prolongation of survival, but with the addition of a

487
00:29:26.488 --> 00:29:30.328
couple of doses of IL-7, all the mice survive free of disease.

488
00:29:30.368 --> 00:29:33.748
And there's a huge expansion of CAR T cells in these mice.

489
00:29:34.888 --> 00:29:38.818
So we said, "Okay, when do you have to add the IL-7?" And so we did a lot of

490
00:29:38.848 --> 00:29:42.788
experiments in immunocompetent and immunodeficient mice and found

491
00:29:42.808 --> 00:29:46.388
that the best time to add the IL-7 was early after the

492
00:29:46.428 --> 00:29:49.608
infusion of the CAR Ts. If you wait

493
00:29:50.308 --> 00:29:54.168
21 days, there's no benefit. If you wait 14 days, there's

494
00:29:54.178 --> 00:29:57.968
a diminished benefit, and you have to give it between days one and

495
00:29:58.008 --> 00:30:01.888
day seven for them to be markedly improved in survival and expansion

496
00:30:01.908 --> 00:30:05.818
of CAR Ts.So that's also a problem for CRS.

497
00:30:05.858 --> 00:30:09.008
And so when we asked the FDA to let us do a clinical

498
00:30:09.068 --> 00:30:12.628
trial with IL-7, the same long-acting IL-7 in

499
00:30:12.668 --> 00:30:14.488
patients, they said, "No, you can't do it.

500
00:30:14.948 --> 00:30:18.408
We won't let you give the drug until day 21." And we said, "At day

501
00:30:18.608 --> 00:30:19.018
21,

502
00:30:19.888 --> 00:30:23.528
by that time, all of the CAR T cells have contracted and there's none

503
00:30:23.588 --> 00:30:27.378
left." And so they said, "Too bad. Do it

504
00:30:27.428 --> 00:30:31.348
anyway." And so we did it, and then we submitted an R01 grant,

505
00:30:31.388 --> 00:30:35.348
and all four reviewers said it had a fatal flaw and that the IL-7

506
00:30:35.388 --> 00:30:36.288
was given too late.

507
00:30:37.328 --> 00:30:41.288
So you can't win. And so we finished this trial, and actually there

508
00:30:41.328 --> 00:30:45.228
was a positive effect. And even though we were given the drug late, and so the

509
00:30:45.308 --> 00:30:46.948
second trial, which is ongoing now,

510
00:30:48.548 --> 00:30:51.548
the FDA let us give the drug between day seven and day 10.

511
00:30:51.948 --> 00:30:55.288
So we're hoping for even more improvement in outcome.

512
00:30:55.488 --> 00:30:59.268
So this is a very simple way to enhance CAR T cell function and maybe

513
00:30:59.328 --> 00:31:03.168
salvage some of those patients that go on to relapse with T-cell ALL and

514
00:31:03.208 --> 00:31:04.868
with T-cell non-Hodgkin's lymphoma.

515
00:31:05.848 --> 00:31:09.028
Okay, the final is the issue of toxicity, which the

516
00:31:09.108 --> 00:31:12.768
FDA was

517
00:31:12.808 --> 00:31:16.248
completely fixated on. So they were very fixated

518
00:31:16.408 --> 00:31:16.868
on

519
00:31:19.368 --> 00:31:21.888
CRS, and they wanted us to be extremely careful.

520
00:31:21.928 --> 00:31:25.508
And so we decided to look into CRS, and

521
00:31:25.568 --> 00:31:28.747
CRS is one of these mythical biologic

522
00:31:28.868 --> 00:31:30.748
processes. It's like HLH

523
00:31:31.908 --> 00:31:35.888
that people talk about, and there are many experts everywhere that

524
00:31:35.928 --> 00:31:38.828
have their own way of treating CRS and HLH.

525
00:31:39.348 --> 00:31:41.568
But really the biology of CRS and

526
00:31:43.748 --> 00:31:47.468
inflammatory reactions and ICANS associated with the CAR Ts is very

527
00:31:47.588 --> 00:31:51.568
poorly understood. So we decided to do a few little experiments to

528
00:31:51.628 --> 00:31:55.228
see if we could understand it a bit and also maybe devise some

529
00:31:56.248 --> 00:31:59.068
maybe intelligent mitigation approaches for CRS.

530
00:31:59.808 --> 00:32:01.188
So the first thing we did, we said

531
00:32:02.228 --> 00:32:03.028
T cell

532
00:32:04.468 --> 00:32:08.308
activation is dependent upon many different

533
00:32:08.328 --> 00:32:12.308
kinases. And so we said, "Let's just screen all

534
00:32:12.328 --> 00:32:15.968
the known kinase inhibitors, serine/threonine kinase and

535
00:32:16.008 --> 00:32:18.528
tyrosine kinase inhibitors that are out there.

536
00:32:19.268 --> 00:32:23.248
And then see if we can actually block CRS without

537
00:32:23.268 --> 00:32:26.908
affecting CAR T cell function." So the assay consisted of a

538
00:32:26.948 --> 00:32:30.477
very simple assay in which we took from the same donor,

539
00:32:31.868 --> 00:32:34.968
myeloid cells that had been primed with GM-CSF,

540
00:32:35.728 --> 00:32:38.848
a target population, which is CD19, these are Ramos

541
00:32:39.508 --> 00:32:42.728
GFP-labeled, and then CAR Ts from the same

542
00:32:43.648 --> 00:32:47.368
patient. And so the CAR Ts kill the Ramos cells, and the

543
00:32:47.508 --> 00:32:49.388
bioluminescent signal disappears.

544
00:32:49.848 --> 00:32:52.768
And in the supernatant, if this induces

545
00:32:52.828 --> 00:32:56.808
a CRS response, we should see IL-6 in

546
00:32:56.848 --> 00:32:59.268
the supernatant. So that's the simple assay.

547
00:32:59.968 --> 00:33:02.968
And so we're looking for drugs in this assay that actually

548
00:33:03.808 --> 00:33:07.788
have no inhibition of CAR T cell function, so down low

549
00:33:07.908 --> 00:33:08.228
on the

550
00:33:09.348 --> 00:33:13.328
Y-axis. And then also have

551
00:33:16.228 --> 00:33:19.328
the percent of IL-6 is also low, and so

552
00:33:19.888 --> 00:33:23.768
towards the zero on the X-axis. So these guys here.

553
00:33:24.228 --> 00:33:27.928
And so when we actually screened 700 kinase inhibitors with multiple

554
00:33:27.988 --> 00:33:31.748
doses, we found that devol Asib, which is a PI3

555
00:33:31.828 --> 00:33:33.068
gamma delta inhibitor,

556
00:33:34.688 --> 00:33:38.628
ruxolitinib, which is a JAK kinase, JAK1,

557
00:33:38.768 --> 00:33:40.488
JAK2 inhibitor, and

558
00:33:41.468 --> 00:33:45.388
inhibitors of the mTOR pathway were the only ones that

559
00:33:45.428 --> 00:33:47.888
ended up in this select group of drugs.

560
00:33:48.728 --> 00:33:52.328
So we said, "Okay, is this true? So let's test devol Asib because it's

561
00:33:52.368 --> 00:33:55.628
approved for the treatment of CLL, and let's test

562
00:33:56.068 --> 00:33:59.488
Jakafi because it's approved for the treatment of

563
00:34:00.688 --> 00:34:04.558
mild proliferative diseases and also for graft-versus-host disease." And we helped

564
00:34:04.568 --> 00:34:08.278
develop this drug for graft-versus-host disease, so we were very familiar with all

565
00:34:08.288 --> 00:34:12.257
the JAK inhibitors. So this is the first experiment showing that

566
00:34:12.268 --> 00:34:15.948
devol Asib dramatically decreases the production

567
00:34:16.048 --> 00:34:18.268
of IL-6 in this assay.

568
00:34:19.548 --> 00:34:22.198
And also, ruxolitinib does the same.

569
00:34:22.607 --> 00:34:25.609
And when you combine the two drugs together, they're synergistic.

570
00:34:25.948 --> 00:34:29.828
So if you really want to block IL-6, you want to block both PI3 gamma

571
00:34:29.908 --> 00:34:33.669
delta and JAK1, JAK2 pathways. And you can see on the

572
00:34:33.708 --> 00:34:34.339
bottom that that

573
00:34:35.569 --> 00:34:39.548
did not result in any significant decrease in CAR T cell function

574
00:34:39.649 --> 00:34:43.109
in this in vitro assay. So we thought maybe these two

575
00:34:43.149 --> 00:34:46.008
pathways could be exploited ultimately clinically.

576
00:34:46.848 --> 00:34:50.408
So we just did a couple of other things that these data have been generated by

577
00:34:50.488 --> 00:34:53.968
other groups such as Marcella Maus, a group from Rome,

578
00:34:54.388 --> 00:34:57.069
showing that the gamma interferon pathway is very important.

579
00:34:57.109 --> 00:35:01.008
We knocked out gamma interferon in the CAR Ts, and as

580
00:35:01.048 --> 00:35:05.008
you might expect, gamma went down as expected, but also IL-6

581
00:35:05.048 --> 00:35:08.868
went down. So this recapitulated two or three other groups that showed that gamma

582
00:35:08.888 --> 00:35:12.848
was a critical piece of the puzzle for CRS.

583
00:35:14.008 --> 00:35:14.248
So

584
00:35:15.268 --> 00:35:18.848
then we did single-cell sequencing because everybody has to do

585
00:35:18.908 --> 00:35:21.028
single-cell sequencing these days.

586
00:35:21.548 --> 00:35:25.468
And so these are the data we showed.

587
00:35:25.828 --> 00:35:29.028
And so what happens is we identified about

588
00:35:29.148 --> 00:35:32.668
four different transcriptional subsets of these

589
00:35:32.728 --> 00:35:36.448
myeloid cells and several subsets of the T cells.

590
00:35:36.978 --> 00:35:40.268
And when you add the target population, these guys here, these

591
00:35:40.408 --> 00:35:43.908
PMC2s, become PMC1s, and the

592
00:35:43.968 --> 00:35:47.288
PMC1s produce all of the IL-6.

593
00:35:47.868 --> 00:35:51.828
And these resting T cells become activated, so they move down in the bottom.

594
00:35:52.288 --> 00:35:54.428
So I'll just show you what happens with the inhibitors.

595
00:35:54.968 --> 00:35:58.448
So when you add the target, these guys that are resting become highly

596
00:35:58.548 --> 00:35:59.128
activated,

597
00:36:00.088 --> 00:36:03.688
and that movement is blocked by those two inhibitors.

598
00:36:04.248 --> 00:36:08.068
And all of these myeloid cells that are not producing any IL-6

599
00:36:08.368 --> 00:36:12.348
move into this PMC1 pathway, which by single-cell RNA-seq

600
00:36:12.788 --> 00:36:15.268
are those cells that produce all the IL-6.

601
00:36:15.388 --> 00:36:18.948
Some IL-6 is produced by these PMC3s, which are

602
00:36:19.048 --> 00:36:22.908
transcriptionally very related to the PMC1s, so they're probably the

603
00:36:22.988 --> 00:36:25.980
same population.So we think that

604
00:36:27.100 --> 00:36:27.260
this

605
00:36:27.940 --> 00:36:31.560
provides

606
00:36:31.620 --> 00:36:35.500
some information into the mechanism. And then what about bispecifics?

607
00:36:35.970 --> 00:36:39.840
So bispecifics is the same thing. We mixed a target

608
00:36:39.920 --> 00:36:43.580
cell, and we put in a myeloid cell, and we put in the CAR T

609
00:36:43.700 --> 00:36:47.400
cell. No, not a CAR T cell. We put in a resting T cell, and we

610
00:36:47.460 --> 00:36:50.940
either added a bispecific or not. So in this case, blinatumomab.

611
00:36:51.440 --> 00:36:54.980
So you can see that when you add blinatumomab, you have a huge increase in

612
00:36:55.080 --> 00:36:57.820
IL-6 production, just like you do with CAR Ts.

613
00:36:58.280 --> 00:37:01.040
And then when you use devolucix, you block that effect.

614
00:37:01.480 --> 00:37:03.100
And it doesn't have any effect on

615
00:37:04.240 --> 00:37:05.360
function of T cells

616
00:37:06.200 --> 00:37:09.880
when you throw in a bispecific and you're looking at tumor killing.

617
00:37:10.360 --> 00:37:14.120
So devolucix and JAK inhibitors probably block or

618
00:37:14.200 --> 00:37:17.000
mitigate CRS without affecting

619
00:37:18.520 --> 00:37:19.720
CAR T cell function

620
00:37:20.800 --> 00:37:23.580
or T cell function in the context of bispecific.

621
00:37:23.650 --> 00:37:27.600
So if you want to mitigate bispecific toxicity, this would be a potential

622
00:37:27.640 --> 00:37:31.290
way. It has to be tested, though, and it requires collaboration,

623
00:37:31.360 --> 00:37:33.420
investment, and some time and effort.

624
00:37:34.180 --> 00:37:36.600
Okay, what about genes and pathways that might

625
00:37:39.420 --> 00:37:41.740
be involved? So we did a CRISPR screen.

626
00:37:41.780 --> 00:37:44.830
This is another obligate kind of thing that people do these days.

627
00:37:44.850 --> 00:37:46.920
And we did a CRISPR screen for all the known genes

628
00:37:47.760 --> 00:37:50.020
that are activated and expressed on T cells.

629
00:37:50.040 --> 00:37:53.890
And we really looked at the genes that were expressed on the surface of T cells,

630
00:37:54.500 --> 00:37:55.240
and might

631
00:37:56.300 --> 00:37:59.860
also be known to be released into the supernatant because our data

632
00:37:59.960 --> 00:38:03.780
supported that this effect on IL-6 production was most

633
00:38:03.820 --> 00:38:06.920
potent when the T cell was in direct

634
00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:10.860
contact with the monocyte. When the T cells were separated

635
00:38:10.900 --> 00:38:11.180
by

636
00:38:13.640 --> 00:38:17.300
any distance, the soluble effects were there, but it wasn't dramatic.

637
00:38:17.720 --> 00:38:21.420
And so we looked at about 300 genes, and we picked the top 20

638
00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:25.680
and the lower 20 that when deleted would result in either

639
00:38:25.740 --> 00:38:26.330
increased

640
00:38:27.520 --> 00:38:28.340
or decreased

641
00:38:29.720 --> 00:38:33.709
IL-6 production. And we looked at all these 20 genes, and we saw that one of them

642
00:38:33.760 --> 00:38:37.640
was very consistent with what we knew about the biology, and that

643
00:38:37.660 --> 00:38:40.300
was CD40. It's expressed on T cells.

644
00:38:40.640 --> 00:38:40.760
It's

645
00:38:42.340 --> 00:38:45.680
upregulated with activated T cells, and it's also

646
00:38:47.480 --> 00:38:48.920
released into the supernatant.

647
00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:53.940
So what we did is we knocked out CD40 ligand in

648
00:38:53.980 --> 00:38:56.840
CAR Ts, and you can see what happens to the IL-6 production.

649
00:38:56.860 --> 00:39:00.050
It goes way down, almost like gamma interferon, to be quite honest.

650
00:39:00.630 --> 00:39:04.520
And if you use a neutralizing antibody to gamma interferon, you see the same

651
00:39:04.560 --> 00:39:07.430
effect. It dramatically reduces the IL-6 production.

652
00:39:07.820 --> 00:39:09.170
So CD40 ligand,

653
00:39:10.420 --> 00:39:14.380
in this assay, it's very critically involved in the IL-6

654
00:39:14.400 --> 00:39:15.080
production.

655
00:39:16.240 --> 00:39:19.420
And then also that didn't have an effect on CAR T cell function.

656
00:39:20.880 --> 00:39:23.700
And then we looked at the effect of CD40 ligand antibody.

657
00:39:23.740 --> 00:39:26.660
These are two different antibodies, and also when we combined

658
00:39:28.100 --> 00:39:31.900
the CD40 ligand antibody with a gamma interferon

659
00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:35.660
antibody, you can see that the IL-6 production is actually below

660
00:39:35.700 --> 00:39:38.800
baseline. So if you really want to knock out

661
00:39:39.240 --> 00:39:43.180
IL-6 production, you either combine a PI3 kinase gamma delta

662
00:39:43.200 --> 00:39:46.700
inhibitor, which actually blocks CD40 ligand

663
00:39:46.780 --> 00:39:50.560
signaling, by the way, and also gamma interferon

664
00:39:50.640 --> 00:39:53.920
signaling. So those two pathways we think are critically involved.

665
00:39:53.960 --> 00:39:57.920
So we did this final experiment, which was an experiment I didn't believe we

666
00:39:57.960 --> 00:40:01.880
should do, and we did it anyway. We separated the CARs

667
00:40:01.920 --> 00:40:05.780
into fours and eights, and we tested them against the target population,

668
00:40:06.340 --> 00:40:10.080
and then CD4 CARs that were directed to CD19

669
00:40:10.120 --> 00:40:13.540
had almost no effect on killing, as you might expect.

670
00:40:13.550 --> 00:40:15.420
These are fours, and so there was no killing.

671
00:40:15.850 --> 00:40:19.120
And the CD8s, which do all the replication and do all the bad

672
00:40:20.620 --> 00:40:24.280
cytotoxicity effects, were replicating like crazy, and they

673
00:40:24.360 --> 00:40:26.800
kill the target cells beautifully, as you would expect.

674
00:40:27.340 --> 00:40:31.200
And then we looked at the production of IL-6, and

675
00:40:31.240 --> 00:40:34.990
it turned out that the fours, which do none of the killing, are

676
00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:37.800
responsible for all of the IL-6 production.

677
00:40:37.900 --> 00:40:38.690
So those fours

678
00:40:40.160 --> 00:40:40.840
generate all the

679
00:40:42.600 --> 00:40:45.420
bad IL-6 in the CRS, and the eights

680
00:40:46.780 --> 00:40:49.820
do all the killing, but they don't have anything to do with IL-6 production.

681
00:40:50.820 --> 00:40:54.760
So we said, "Why?" And so we looked at by flow cytometry, and we showed

682
00:40:54.780 --> 00:40:58.760
that activated eights express almost no 40 ligand

683
00:40:59.180 --> 00:41:02.440
and activated fours produced a lot of CD40 ligand.

684
00:41:02.920 --> 00:41:06.760
And then we transduced CD8s, which don't

685
00:41:06.780 --> 00:41:09.960
express any 40 ligand with CD40 ligand and with a

686
00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:12.100
protease-resistant CD40 ligand.

687
00:41:12.160 --> 00:41:15.420
So it's expressed on the surface but can't be

688
00:41:15.520 --> 00:41:17.220
proteolytically clipped off the surface.

689
00:41:17.260 --> 00:41:20.700
And remember I told you this direct interaction is most important.

690
00:41:20.770 --> 00:41:22.840
And you can see that when you look at the 40

691
00:41:22.880 --> 00:41:26.520
ligand-transduced CD8s, you get a ton of

692
00:41:26.560 --> 00:41:30.420
secreted CD40 ligand, as you would expect, but you also get a huge

693
00:41:30.500 --> 00:41:34.240
amount of IL-6 produced. And when you look at the CD40

694
00:41:34.280 --> 00:41:37.760
ligand protease-resistant expression, you have a huge amount of

695
00:41:37.840 --> 00:41:41.100
IL-6 and very little secreted CD40 ligand.

696
00:41:41.160 --> 00:41:41.260
So

697
00:41:42.260 --> 00:41:45.800
supports the notion that CD40 ligand membrane-bound is really

698
00:41:45.820 --> 00:41:49.600
important. And membrane-bound CD40 ligand is in trimeric

699
00:41:49.660 --> 00:41:53.570
form. And I'm not going to show you, but trimeric CD40 ligand directly

700
00:41:53.600 --> 00:41:56.730
induces IL-6 production by these monocytes.

701
00:41:57.800 --> 00:42:00.980
And the final thing is we all know that NK cells don't induce any

702
00:42:01.020 --> 00:42:02.660
CRS. Why is that?

703
00:42:03.530 --> 00:42:06.560
It turns out that NK cells produce a ton of gamma interferon.

704
00:42:07.160 --> 00:42:10.540
Everybody knows that. We've all measured gamma interferon in NK

705
00:42:10.580 --> 00:42:14.570
cells. So we thought, "What's going on here?" And so we looked at

706
00:42:14.600 --> 00:42:18.480
CD40 ligand and NK cells, and they don't express any CD40

707
00:42:18.520 --> 00:42:19.970
ligand on the surface. There's

708
00:42:20.020 --> 00:42:23.920
something going on with NK cells

709
00:42:23.940 --> 00:42:27.900
that we haven't figured out yet. Not only do they not express any CD40 ligand

710
00:42:27.940 --> 00:42:31.370
on the surface, but when we transduce NK cells with

711
00:42:31.420 --> 00:42:35.000
CD40 ligand, we can't get CD40 ligand to end up on the

712
00:42:35.010 --> 00:42:38.380
surface. So there's some internal pathway to prevent that from happening.

713
00:42:38.420 --> 00:42:42.060
We don't know why, but that's probably why NK cell

714
00:42:42.760 --> 00:42:46.730
CARs don't induce CRS.All right. We went on

715
00:42:46.750 --> 00:42:50.440
and did two randomized studies. We did a randomized study with idasitnib, which is

716
00:42:50.550 --> 00:42:54.430
a JAK inhibitor, and showed that this JAK inhibitor resulted

717
00:42:54.450 --> 00:42:57.650
in much less CRS than without a JAK inhibitor.

718
00:42:57.670 --> 00:42:59.549
This was recently published

719
00:43:01.110 --> 00:43:04.770
in "Blood." And we also did the same with devol Asib, which was recently

720
00:43:05.010 --> 00:43:08.530
presented at ASH, and that showed that there's almost no

721
00:43:08.590 --> 00:43:12.310
CRS, no grade two, grade three, or grade four CRS in our

722
00:43:12.350 --> 00:43:14.810
patients receiving devol Asib prophylaxis.

723
00:43:14.870 --> 00:43:16.370
So there are pathways forward.

724
00:43:17.510 --> 00:43:21.110
So in conclusion, UCAR T7 and UCAR T2 are effective at killing

725
00:43:21.190 --> 00:43:24.550
T-cell ALL and T-cell non-Hodgkin's lymphoma in vitro and in vivo.

726
00:43:24.599 --> 00:43:28.390
And UCAR T2 must be epitope masked for optimal

727
00:43:28.510 --> 00:43:29.390
treatment

728
00:43:30.710 --> 00:43:33.690
of T-cell non-Hodgkin's lymphoma and relapsed T-cell ALL.

729
00:43:34.810 --> 00:43:38.330
NTi-7 or IL-7 and other synthetic

730
00:43:38.630 --> 00:43:42.310
